text=:Category: SignLanguage%0a:Expansion: Distinguish accents and dialects in sign language%0a:Author: yuluz%0a:Original: [[Articles.AccentsOfSignLanguage|AccentsOfSignLanguage]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.BrandonN|BrandonN]]%0a:Section: C%0a:Completed: 08.05.2021 - 15:27%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-024119-200880#%0a* [-10.05.2021 - 19:41-] || TA_lili marked as complete%0a#foxend 210511-024119-200880#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aOne question that intrigues me a lot regarding sign language if how we distinguish between accents and dialects. I think after reading and researching, I would say that if there is stylistic difference but mutual intelligibility between variations of sign languages, then we can consider them to be different accents. While if there are certain words or grammars that differ but the intelligibility is retained to a large extent, then we would consider those variations as dialects.  %0a%0aJust to give an example of dialects in sign language: some researchers consider Auslan and New Zealand Sign Language as dialects of the British sign Language because they use the same grammar, the same manual alphabet, and much of the same vocabulary, so their mutual intelligibility is retaine. Nevertheless, there are also differences between these variations, like New Zealand Sign Language having signs for Māori words. %0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_lili:)
